Mr Maepherson was himself in the Isle where the hereditary sennachies, of whom I have been speaking, resided for several centuries: he saw the friends of these sennachies, and saw Clanranald. whether he has procur- ed any old papers fit for his purpose from these people, he v can inform you best.

As to your second question, I hope to give you some sa- tisfaction within a little time. I shall make the strictest enquiry for all the persons within twenty miles of my house, who can rehearse, from memory, any part of the poems contained in Mr Macpherson’s Fingal, &a His Temora I have not been able to procure. Ι have begun this work already, and entertain hopes, to me very pleas- ing, that my endeavours will be attended with some suc- cess. Your commands with regard to the exactness of the translation, the pages of the book, and the names of the >persons who rehearse from memory, shall be faithfully executed.

I fancy there is no great difficulty in showing how such compositions have been transmitted from one generation to another. The degree of credit due to such traditionary re- cords as have preserved them, I shall in my next letter place in the justest and best light possible.

The people in the western parts of Ross-shire, know a great deal more concerning the old heroic poemS, or epic fragments, of the Gaelic tongue, than our islanders of the Α northern quarter.
